                                <body>                                                
                                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.—<name type="person">Private John P. Patterson</name>, <name type="organization">Co. A, 49th
                                                                Pennsylvania Volunteers</name>, aged 19 years, was
                                                                wounded at <name type="battle" key="15">Rappahannock Station, Virginia</name>,
                                                                <date type="injury" when="1863-11-07">November 7th, 1863</date>, by a conoidal ball, which
                                                  fractured and depressed both tables of the left
                                                  parietal bone near the vertex.  He was conveyed to
                                                  <name type="place" key="#Washington">Washington</name>, and admitted into the <name type="hospital" key="175">Stanton Hospital</name>
                                                  on <date type="operation" when="1863-11-09"><date type="admit" when="1863-11-09">the 9th</date></date>.  Several fragments of bone were removed
                                                  exposing the dura mater. For two days convulsions
                                                  occurred; after that the patient became tranquil,
                                                  with the loss of voluntary motion in the right arm
                                                  and leg.  On the 20th, the paralysis disappeared.
                                                  The wound suppurated moderately and filled with
                                                  healthy granulations.  On <date type="operation" when="1863-12-26">the 26th</date>, and again on
                                                  <date type="operation" when="1863-12-27"> the 27th of December</date>, several small spiculæ of
                                                                bone were removed. By <date type="injury" when="1864-01-01">January 1st, 1864</date>, the
                                                  patient had entirely recovered; was furloughed on
                                                                <date type="furlough" when="1864-01-07">the 7th</date>, and admitted to <name type="hospital">Turner's Lane Hospital, Philadelphia</name>, on <date type="admit" when="1864-05-11">May 11th</date>.  Epilepsy supervened, and he was discharged from the service on <date type="servicedischarge" when="1864-07-18">July
                                                                  18th, 1864</date>.  A communication from the <name type="person" key="xx">Commissioner
                                                                    of Pensions</name>, dated <date type="pension" when="1868-01-02">January 2d, 1868</date>, states that
                                                  Patterson is a pensioner, and that his disability
                                                  is rated total and permanent.   The case is reported
                                                  by <name type="person">Acting Assistant Surgeon C. Campbell</name>.</p>                                                
